04888nam a22006855i 9780812290073DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)945230988  a97808122900737 a10.9783/97808122900732doi  a(DE-B1597)449875  a(OCoLC)891157744  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0190002bisacsh04a821/.3093572231 aJacobson, Miriam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBarbarous Antiquity :bReorienting the Past in the Poetry of Early Modern England /cMiriam Jacobson. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2014] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b13 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction. Trafficking with Antiquity: Trade, Poetry, and Remediation -- tPart I. Barbarian Invasions -- tChapter 1. Strange Language: Imported Words in Jonson’s Ars Poetica -- tChapter 2. Shaping Subtlety: Sugar in The Arte of English Poesie -- tPart II. Redeeming Ovid -- tChapter 3. Publishing Pain: Zero in The Rape of Lucrece -- tChapter 4. Breeding Fame: Horses and Bulbs in Venus and Adonis -- tPart III. Reorienting Antiquity -- tChapter 5. On Chapman Crossing Marlowe’s Hellespont: Pearls, Dyes, and Ink in Hero and Leander -- tEpilogue. The Peregrinations of Barbarous Antiquity -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the late sixteenth century, English merchants and diplomats ventured into the eastern Mediterranean to trade directly with the Turks, the keepers of an important emerging empire in the Western Hemisphere, and these initial exchanges had a profound effect on English literature. While the theater investigated representations of religious and ethnic identity in its portrayals of Turks and Muslims, poetry, Miriam Jacobson argues, explored East-West exchanges primarily through language and the material text. Just as English markets were flooded with exotic goods, so was the English language awash in freshly imported words describing items such as sugar, jewels, plants, spices, paints, and dyes, as well as technological advancements such as the use of Arabic numerals in arithmetic and the concept of zero.Even as these Eastern words and imports found their way into English poetry, poets wrestled with paying homage to classical authors and styles. In Barbarous Antiquity, Jacobson reveals how poems adapted from Latin or Greek sources and set in the ancient classical world were now reoriented to reflect a contemporary, mercantile Ottoman landscape. As Renaissance English writers including Shakespeare, Jonson, Marlowe, and Chapman weighed their reliance on classical poetic models against contemporary cultural exchanges, a new form of poetry developed, positioned at the crossroads of East and West, ancient and modern. Building each chapter around the intersection of an Eastern import and a classical model, Jacobson shows how Renaissance English poetry not only reconstructed the classical past but offered a critique of that very enterprise with a new set of words and metaphors imported from the East.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aLiterature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311066593240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229007340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812290073423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812290073.jpg  a978-3-11-066593-2  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015